<TITLE> Germany set to scrap Munich Transrapid:source </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BERLIN, March 27 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Germany is set to drop plans to build a flagship high-speed rail link between the Bavarian capital Munich and its airport because of a cost overrun, a source in the country's ruling coalition said on Thursday. The Transrapid, one of the world's fastest trains, was developed by German engineers at Siemens AG and ThyssenKrupp AG and so far the technology has only been used commercially in China. An industry source told Reuters the cost of realising the magnetic-levitation Transrapid link had risen to around 3 billion euros ($4.7 billion) compared with the 1.85 billion originally earmarked for it in 2002. Originally, the federal government had said it would assume up to 925 million euros in costs and Bavaria around 500 million. National rail operator Deutsche Bahn AG had been due to foot some 235 million euros, Munich airport 100 million, the European Union 50 million and Siemens and ThyssenKrupp 25 million each. The project was announced last year by then Bavarian premier Edmund Stoiber just before he stood down as head of the southern state's conservative party in September and his critics said it was a pet project. The plans for the Transrapid, which set a speed record of 450 kph in 1993, faced fierce opposition from some local residents and the Munich mayor. Another plan to build a Transrapid link between Hamburg and Berlin has already been scrapp
